Qualifying standards for World Maters Championships 2019

Marianne Huebner et al

22 September 2018

1 Trend in participation in IWF world championships across years

The increase in women participations has been seen in US National competitions for a while, so that the number of women surpassed those of the number of men in recent years. In particular, among the US athletes in Barcelona the women weightlifters outnumbered the men weightlifters as was also the case for a couple of other countries.

2 Age and Bodyweight distribution

Due the body weight and age distributions it is reasonable to calculate qualifying totals [in kg] based on SMF cutoff values calculated for the top body weight in each weight class and the youngest age in each age class. A decision needs to be made for the heaviest weight classes. In this document the reference weight was 125 kg for men and 105kg for women.

3 SMF distribution

Note the histograms are stacked on top of each other.

It looks like there is a bimodal distribution for men (200-330 and 330-450) and for women (120-180 and 180-250).

3.1 Tables of participants while categorizing bodyweights into the new IWF weight categories

This indicates that the most pressure is in the younger age groups in the middle weight categories.

4 SMF cutoffs, qualifying totals, and number of participants

Comment: A Poisson regression model to predict the number of lifters in each age/weight category showed that of the three predictors age, weight, and SMF, only the age group plays a statistically significant role. That means there are more lifters in the younger age groups. The larger numbers of the middle body weight classes seen in the younger age groups are too few cells, so that body weight did not reach statistical significance to predict the number of lifters. Thus is would be acceptable to focus on qualifying standards by age category only.
